@node introduction "Introduction"
@prev introduction
@next features
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Introduction to DirSize.@{uu}@{ub}

  Here is another one of those tools Commodore missed (I would say  AT,  but
  they  have yet to do anything with the OS). If you are the owner of a hard
  drive, or similar storage devices, you may often wish to know the size  of
  a,  or  several,  directories.  The trouble is, with the commands supplied
  with the OS, you can't. True, you  could  use  @{b}list  <dir>  all@{ub}  but  this
  returns the blocks used, which is not the best unit - most people are more
  familiar with bytes, kilobytes, etc.

  This is where a program like @{b}DirSize@{ub} is useful. It quickly accumulates the
  sizes of the files inside a directory and it's sub-directories.

  There is a number of similar tools available on Aminet and  elsewhere,  so
  why  make  another  one?  The reason is simple: I was bored! I couldn't be
  bothered to download one of the already available tools, so I wrote  this.
  I  have been using it for over a year now, without any problems (even with
  a relatively harmless Mungwall hit which has now disappeared).

@endnode
@node features "Features"
@prev introduction
@next requirements
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Features of DirSize.@{uu}@{ub}

  @{" * " link keyword_sizetype}

  @{" * " link keyword_sizetype} Select the unit of measurement (bytes, kilobytes, megabytes, gigabytes,
       blocks) or select automatically.

  @{" * " link keyword_format} Configure the output in anyway you wish.

  @{" * " link keyword_pattern} Include only files matching a certain AmigaDOS pattern.

    *  Accumulate number of files and directories.

  @{" * " link keyword_dir} Find size of multiple directories according to an AmigaDOS pattern.

  @{" * " link envvar} Setup  a  default  configuration  by  using  a  number  of   environment
       variables.

    *  Extensive support for batch files.

  @{" * " link keyword_sort} Sort (ascending/descending) output.

  @{" * " link keyword_verbose} Show all sub-directories.

@endnode
@node requirements "Requirements"
@prev features
@next installation
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Requirements for DirSize.@{uu}@{ub}

  @{b}DirSize@{ub} requires the following:

  Workbench 2.04+. (version 37+ of dos.library)
  Shell/CLI experience.

  Commodore's/AT's  Installer  program  is  needed  for   installation   via
  Installer script.

@endnode
@node installation "Installation"
@prev requirements
@next usage
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Installation of DirSize.@{uu}@{ub}

  The simplest method of installation  is  to  use  the  provided  Installer
  script. Installer program is required for this to work.

  To install by hand, just copy the  executable  (called  @{b}DirSize@{ub})  to  your
  desired location. You might want to copy the documentation elsewhere.

@endnode
@node usage "Usage"
@prev installation
@next keyword_dir
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Usage of DirSize.@{uu}@{ub}

  Currently, @{b}DirSize@{ub} is a Shell/CLI only tool. It is my intention to give it
  a user-interface (see @{"future" link future}).

  The command line template of @{b}DirSize@{ub} is as follows:
 
  DIR/M,WILD=WILDCARD/K,P=PATTERN/K,B=BYTES/S,KB=KILOBYTES/S,MB=MEGABYTES/S,
  GB=GIGABYTES/S,BLOCKS/S,AUTO/S,HEADER/K,FOOTER/N/K,RECURSE/K,VERBOSE/K,
  FP=FLOATINGPOINT/K,SEP=SEPARATORS/K,FORMAT/K,FOOTFORMAT/K,CONFIG/K,TO/K,
  SORT/K,ASCEND/K

  If  you  have  any  experience  of  AmigaDOS  templates,  many  should  be
  self-explanatory.

  @{" DIR/M              " link keyword_dir}
  @{" WILD=WILDCARD/K    " link keyword_wildcard} (Obsolete)
  @{" P=PATTERN/K        " link keyword_pattern}
  @{" B=BYTES/S          " link keyword_sizetype}
  @{" KB=KILOBYTES/S     " link keyword_sizetype}
  @{" MB=MEGABYTES/S     " link keyword_sizetype}
  @{" GB=GIGABYTES/S     " link keyword_sizetype}
  @{" BLOCKS/S           " link keyword_sizetype}
  @{" AUTO/S             " link keyword_sizetype}
  @{" HEADER/K           " link keyword_header} New for 1.7
  @{" FOOTER/N/K         " link keyword_footer}
  @{" RECURSE/K          " link keyword_recurse}
  @{" VERBOSE/K          " link keyword_verbose} New for 1.7
  @{" FP=FLOATINGPOINT/K " link keyword_floatingpoint}
  @{" SEP=SEPARATORS/K   " link keyword_separators}
  @{" FORMAT/K           " link keyword_format}
  @{" FOOTFORMAT/K       " link keyword_format}
  @{" CONFIG/K           " link keyword_config}
  @{" TO/K               " link keyword_to} New for 1.7
  @{" SORT/K             " link keyword_sort} New for 1.7
  @{" ASCEND/K           " link keyword_ascend} New for 1.7

  From version 1.6 of @{b}DirSize@{ub}, an @{"environment variable" link envvar} can be used to  store
  your  favourite  settings.  This  is  particularly  useful  when  used  in
  conjunction with the @{"FORMAT" link keyword_format} and @{"FOOTFORMAT" link keyword_format} keywords.

  Once each directory has been scanned, the program will output the size  of
  the directory together with the number of files and sub-directories inside
  it.

  At the end of this, the total size, number of files and  directories  will
  be  displayed.  This  is,  basically, the sum of the figures given for the
  individual directories.

  If you wish to abort the scanning of directories, it is possible to send a
  break command by pressing @{b}Ctrl-C@{ub}, which will stop the operation.

  See also: @{"Examples" link examples}.

@endnode
@node keyword_dir "DIR/M"
@prev usage
@next keyword_wildcard
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: DIR/M.@{uu}@{ub}

  Specify the directories you wish to count. If none  are  given,  then  the
  current directory is used.

  When using the @{"environment variables" link envvar}, it is possible to preset a  list  of
  directories you wish to scan before the command line ones are scanned. The
  first directories are those given in the @{"main environment  variable" link envvar},  then
  the @{"custom variable" link keyword_config}.

  Also supported is pattern matching. For example, you  may  have  organised
  your music directory alphabetically such that it looks like this:

    Directory "DH1:Music/" on Friday 23-Aug-96
    TunesA                       Dir ----rwed 09-Aug-96 15:38:32
    TunesB                       Dir ----rwed 09-Aug-96 15:40:35
    TunesC                       Dir ----rwed 14-Apr-96 21:17:17
    ...

  Say you wanted to find the sizes of each directory. You  could  enter  the
  command:

  @{b}DirSize DH1:Music/TunesA DH1:Music/TunesB DH1:Music/TunesC@{ub} etc.

  This would give you the desired result, but is  tedious.  Version  1.5  of
  @{b}DirSize@{ub}  introduces  pattern matching for directories. Therefore it is now
  possible to enter:

  @{b}DirSize DH1:Music/Tunes?@{ub}

  or maybe,

  @{b}DirSize DH1:Music/Tunes#?@{ub}

  Both of which will also give the desired result, but with less typing. The
  second example would also find directories beginning with 'Tunes' with any
  number of characters following.

  If you wish to find a subset of  this  directory,  e.g.  only  directories
  TunesD, TunesQ, and TunesZ, you would enter:

  @{b}DirSize DH1:Music/Tunes(D|Q|Z)@{ub}

  The pattern matching is  performed  by  AmigaDOS.  For  those  interested,
  MatchFirst()/MatchNext()/MatchEnd() calls are made.

  It is possible to disable this feature by placing  an  apostraphe  (')  in
  front of the wildcard character you wish to disable. For example,

  @{b}DirSize DH1:A?#c@{ub}

  Would match directories such as @{i}Abcccc@{ui}, @{i}Axc@{ui}, @{i}Az@{ui} etc. whereas

  @{b}DirSize DH1:A?'#c@{ub}

  Would match directories with names like @{i}Ab#c@{ui}, @{i}Ax#c@{ui},  @{i}Az#c@{ui},  etc.  Meaning,
  the '#' is treated as a normal character.

  Default: current directory

@endnode
@node keyword_wildcard "WILD=WILDCARD/K"
@prev keyword_dir
@next keyword_pattern
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: WILD=WILDCARD/K (obsolete).@{uu}@{ub}

  The @{b}WILDCARD@{ub} keyword is used to enable or  disable  any  pattern  matching
  used  in  the  @{"DIR" link keyword_dir}  keyword  (not the @{"PATTERN" link keyword_pattern} keyword). It is of a boolean
  type.

  Please note that this keyword is considered obsolete and will  be  removed
  in the next release. The reason is given below:

  I have since discovered that  it  is  possible  to  disable  wildcards  by
  placing  an  apostraphe (') in front of the wildcard character you wish to
  disable. For example,

  @{b}DirSize DH1:A?#c@{ub}

  Would match directories such as @{i}Abcccc@{ui}, @{i}Axc@{ui}, @{i}Az@{ui} etc. whereas

  @{b}DirSize DH1:A?'#c@{ub}

  Would match directories with names like @{i}Ab#c@{ui}, @{i}Ax#c@{ui},  @{i}Az#c@{ui},  etc.  Meaning,
  the '#' is treated as a normal character.

  See also: @{"Boolean values" link boolean}.

  Default: wildcards (pattern matching) is enabled.

@endnode
@node keyword_pattern "P=PATTERN/K"
@prev keyword_wildcard
@next keyword_sizetype
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: P=PATTERN/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  It is possible to  include  (or  exclude)  files  which  match  the  given
  AmigaDOS  pattern.  For  example,  if  you  wish  to find the size of your
  archive directory, counting only archives, you  could  use  the  following
  command:

  @{b}DirSize archives/ PATTERN=#?.(lha|lzx)@{ub}

  As of version 1.6, it is now possible to give a  full  filename  and  only
  that file will be counted. This means you can type:

  @{b}DirSize C: PATTERN=AddDataTypes@{ub}

  and  only  that  file  will  be  counted, as if it was the only one in the
  directory. Not a major enhancement, but is more complete.

  Default: all files are included in count (equivalent to #?).

@endnode
@node keyword_sizetype "B=BYTES/S,KB=KILOBYTES/S,MB=MEGABYTES/S,GB=GIGABYTES/S,AUTO/S"
@prev keyword_pattern
@next keyword_header
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keywords: B=BYTES/S,KB=KILOBYTES/S,MB=MEGABYTES/S,GB=GIGABYTES/S,BLOCKS/S,@{uu}@{ub}
  @{b}@{u}AUTO/S.@{uu}@{ub}

  These are all switches but only one should be used (the right most in  the
  template  has  priority  over  those  on the left, if you do use more than
  one). Specifying @{b}BYTES@{ub} (or @{b}B@{ub}) will cause @{b}DirSize@{ub} to output sizes in bytes,
  @{b}KB@{ub}  will  output  kilobytes,  etc. @{b}AUTO@{ub} will cause the program to select a
  suitable size for each directory.

  It is important to remember that you can only specify  one  unit  for  all
  directories.  If  you  request  @{b}KILOBYTES@{ub}, sizes of directories will be in
  kilobytes. The only exception to this is @{b}AUTO@{ub}.

  The @{b}BLOCKS@{ub} keyword is an unusual size type in  that  it  only  appears  if
  specified,  not  through the @{b}AUTO@{ub} keyword. Blocks are used in the AmigaDOS
  file system. One block is made of at most 1024 bytes.  An  empty  file  is
  contained  in  one  block,  as is a file of length 1023 bytes. A 1024 byte
  file is made of two blocks.

  The @{b}list@{ub} command uses a slightly different method to this, so will  return
  different  results. It seems blocks are assumed to be of 512 bytes, rather
  than 1024.

  Default: @{b}AUTO@{ub}.

@endnode
@node keyword_header "HEADER/K"
@prev keyword_sizetype
@next keyword_footer
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: HEADER/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  Before any sizes are printed, whatever string is here  is  printed  first.
  Allows, for example, titles above columns of text.

  A  header  with  no  characters  (use @{b}HEADER=""@{ub}) will result in the header
  being disabled).

  For example:

  @{b}HEADER="Path         Size     Files   Directories"@{ub}

  Default: no header is printed.

  See also: @{"FOOTER/K" link keyword_footer}, @{"FOOTFORMAT/K" link keyword_format}

@endnode
@node keyword_footer "FOOTER/N/K"
@prev keyword_header
@next keyword_recurse
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: FOOTER/N/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  By default, the footer (which contains information on the total  size  and
  number  of  directories  counted)  appears only if two or more directories
  were specified on the command line.  It  would  appear  pointless  if  the
  footer was included when no or only one directory was counted.

  It is possible to  control  this  by  specifying  the  minimum  number  of
  directories to count, after which the footer would be shown at the end.

  If the value is 0 or less, then  the  footer  is  disabled.  There  is  no
  hard-coded maximum.

  For example,

  @{b}DirSize C: DEVS: FOOTER=0@{ub}

  Only prints the sizes of C: and DEVS: (if they both exist). No  footer  is
  displayed.

  @{b}DirSize DH1:Pics/#? FOOTER=5@{ub}

  Prints the sizes of all directories inside  the  DH1:Pics/  directory.  If
  more than five are counted, a footer is displayed.

  Default: Footer appears on two or more directories.

  See also: @{"FOOTFORMAT/K" link keyword_format}

@endnode
@node keyword_recurse "RECURSE/K"
@prev keyword_footer
@next keyword_verbose
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: RECURSE/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  By default, @{b}DirSize@{ub} scans sub-directories. This was the main  idea  behind
  the  program!  You  can  prevent  this by setting the @{b}RECURSE@{ub} keyword to a
  negative value (see @{"Boolean values" link boolean}).

  Default: Recursion is enabled.

  See also: @{"Boolean values" link boolean}

@endnode
@node keyword_verbose "VERBOSE/K"
@prev keyword_recurse
@next keyword_floatingpoint
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: VERBOSE/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  This keyword  makes  @{b}DirSize@{ub}  behave  more  like  the  UNIX  command,  @{b}du@{ub}.
  Basically,  if  enabled,  every  sub-directory  of  the ones @{"given" link keyword_dir} will be
  displayed. This command takes a @{"Boolean" link boolean} parameter.

  When verbose mode is enabled, sub-directories  are  not  included  in  the
  count  for  when  the  footer  should  be  displayed. Even if there are 50
  sub-directories, if @{"FOOTER" link keyword_footer} is not set to a suitable value, no footer  will
  be displayed.

  A sideeffect of this keyword is that you can now view an  entire  tree  of
  directories by using the following command:

  @{b}DirSize <dir> VERBOSE ON FORMAT="%p" FOOTER=0@{ub}

  Currently, the full path of the directories will be shown.  This  is  what
  dos.library's NameFromLock() call returns and I'll work to change this for
  the next release.

  Default: Output is terse (VERBOSE=OFF).

  See also: @{"Boolean values" link boolean}

@endnode
@node keyword_floatingpoint "FP=FLOATINGPOINT/K"
@prev keyword_verbose
@next keyword_separators
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: FP=FLOATINGPOINT/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  When displaying sizes in units such as kilobytes  and  megabytes,  @{b}DirSize@{ub}
  may add a fractional part to the number to give a better representation of
  the size of directories.

  This can be disabled by  using  the  @{b}FLOATINGPOINT@{ub}  keyword.  Providing  a
  negative value prevents a floating point being displayed, a positive value
  does the opposite. See @{"Boolean values" link boolean} for more information on this.

  If floating points are enabled, separators are disabled on sizes.

  Default: Floating points are enabled.

  See also: @{"Boolean values" link boolean}

@endnode
@node keyword_separators "SEP=SEPARATORS/K"
@prev keyword_floatingpoint
@next keyword_format
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: SEP=SEPARATORS/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  This  feature  is  only  available  on  systems  where  locale.library  is
  available.

  Separators are used to make numbers  clearer,  by  inserting  a  character
  between  groups  of  numbers. In the UK, commas are used. For example, the
  number, 123456789 will be displayed as 123,456,789.

  Setting @{b}SEPARATORS@{ub} to a  positive  value  enables  separators,  whereas  a
  negative  value  will  do  the  opposite.  See  @{"Boolean  values" link boolean}  for  more
  information.

  Separators will not appear in sizes if floating points are enabled.

  Default: Separators are enabled. They don't appear for sizes  if  floating
  points are enabled.

  See also: @{"Boolean values" link boolean}

@endnode
@node keyword_format "FORMAT/K,FOOTFORMAT/K"
@prev keyword_separators
@next format_examples
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keywords: FORMAT/K,FOOTFORMAT/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  These two keywords allow for customising the output of @{b}DirSize@{ub}. They  work
  in a similar way to the @{b}LFORMAT@{ub} keyword of the @{b}list@{ub} command.

  Whatever is placed in the string is output to  the  screen.  Commands  are
  introduced  by  a  '%'  character  and  most have parameters which must be
  placed after the '%' character and before the command itself.  The  parser
  is case insensitive. For example, @{b}%abbr_u@{ub} and @{b}%ABBR_U@{ub} are the same.

  The difference between the @{b}FORMAT@{ub} and @{b}FOOTFORMAT@{ub}  keywords  is  only  that
  @{b}FORMAT@{ub}  specifies  the output for the sizes of individual directories, and
  the @{b}FOOTFORMAT@{ub} is for the footer, displaying the totals.

  The commands available are listed below, along with their parameters.


  @{b}- %P  Path of directory@{ub}

    Outputs the directory path. If the current directory is  being  scanned,
    the  complete  path  is  displayed.  This  is ignored for the FOOTFORMAT
    keyword.

    @{i}Parameters:@{ui}

      None


  @{b}- %S  Size of directory@{ub}

    Outputs the size of the current directory  being  scanned  or,  for  the
    footer, the total size of all directories scanned.

    @{i}Parameters:@{ui}

      @{b}- Unit types: B, K, M, G, L, A.@{ub}

        Force size to a specific type.

        B specifies bytes
        K specifies kilobytes
        M specifies megabytes
        G specifies gigabytes
        L specifies blocks
        A specifies automatic selection

      @{b}- FP and NOFP@{ub}

        This enables (@{b}FP@{ub}) or disables (@{b}NOFP@{ub}) floating points in  the  output
        of the size of a directory.

      @{b}- SEP and NOSEP@{ub}

        This enables (@{b}SEP@{ub}) or disables (@{b}NOSEP@{ub}) separators in the  output  of
        numerical values.


  @{b}- %U  Unit (e.g. Bytes, Blocks, Megabytes, etc.)@{ub}

    Outputs a unit  name.  This  command  is  linked  to  the  %s  (size  of
    directory) command.

    @{i}Parameters:@{ui}

      @{b}- Unit types: B, K, M, G, L, A.@{ub}

        Force unit name to a specific type.

        B specifies bytes
        K specifies kilobytes
        M specifies megabytes
        G specifies gigabytes
        L specifies blocks
        A specifies automatic selection

      @{b}- ABBR@{ub}

        Outputs an abbreviated version of the unit type.

        @{u}Non-abbreviated@{uu}  =>  @{u}Abbreviated@{uu}
        Bytes            =>  B
        Kilobytes        =>  Kb
        Megabytes        =>  Mb
        Gigabytes        =>  Gb
        Blocks           =>  Blks


  @{b}- %F  Number of files@{ub}

    Outputs the number of files counted in the directory being  scanned  or,
    for the footer, the total number of files counted.

    @{i}Parameters:@{ui}

      @{b}- SEP and NOSEP@{ub}

        This enables (@{b}SEP@{ub}) or disables (@{b}NOSEP@{ub}) separators  in  the  output  of
        numerical values.


  @{b}- %D  Number of directories@{ub}

    Same as %f (number of files) only for directories.

    @{i}Parameters:@{ui}

      @{b}- SEP and NOSEP@{ub}

        This enables (@{b}SEP@{ub}) or disables (@{b}NOSEP@{ub}) separators in the  output  of
        numerical values.


  @{b}- %%  Percentage sign@{ub}

    This command is supplied for completeness. It just outputs a  percentage
    sign ('%').

    @{i}Parameters:@{ui}

      None.


  Additional parameters available to all commands (excluding %%):

    @{b}- Width: -nnn@{ub}

    To print in nicely formatted columns, you can enter  a  number,  causing
    text  to  be  padded with spaces to fit the width specified. By default,
    the text is right justified, though preceding  the  number  with  a  '-'
    character  forces  left justification. The number may be of a maximum of
    three characters long, thus allowing a range of 0  to  999.  The  number
    should be entered as a decimal number.

  Having many parameters in a command can make it look unreadable.  This  is
  why  I  have  added  the ability to separate parameters with an underscore
  character ('_'). If the command parser comes across one of  these,  it  is
  ignored, and reads the following characters.

  An error in the command will result it in being ignored. For  example,  if
  you  specify you want abbreviated path names (@{b}%abbr_p@{ub}), which is something
  not (yet?) supported, will cause no path at all to be  printed.  Similarly
  with  ambiguous  commands  (for  example,  @{b}%fp_nofp_s@{ub},  meaning you want a
  floating point and no floating points for the size output).

  See also: @{"Examples" link format_examples}

  Much of this feature (being able to control what was printed) is based  on
  the ideas of Herzen haben Fluegel. My idea was making it into an 'LFORMAT'
  type switch.

  Defaults:
        FORMAT: @{b}%-25p %10s %-9u  [Files: %4f  Dirs: %4d]@{ub}
    FOOTFORMAT: @{b}Total: %s %u (%ls %labbru) [Files: %f  Dirs: %d]@{ub}

@endnode
@node format_examples "FORMAT and FOOTFORMAT Examples"
@prev keyword_format
@next keyword_config
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Examples of FORMAT and FOOTFORMAT.@{uu}@{ub}

  The @{"FORMAT" link keyword_format} and @{"FOOTFORMAT" link keyword_format} keywords warrant some examples of their own:

  To output only the number of files and directories without separators:

    @{b}FORMAT="Files: %nosepf Directories: %NOSEP_D"@{ub}

  The following outputs the sizes of directories using different units.  The
  first  command  is the path name, followed by the size and unit (using the
  default type) then kilobytes and finally in blocks (on a newline).

    @{b}FORMAT="*"%p*" %s %u; %ks %ku; %ls %lu*n%ls %labbru"@{ub}

  Note: the *" and *n are used by AmigaDOS to output quotes and newlines.

  To print the sizes of directories in columns:

    @{b}FORMAT="%-25p %10bs %10ks %10ms"@{ub}

  More examples will be added in the due course.

@endnode
@node keyword_config "CONFIG/K"
@prev format_examples
@next to
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: CONFIG/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  A second environment variable, only you can decide on the name.

  See also: @{"Environment variable" link envvar}

@endnode
@node keyword_to "TO/K"
@prev keyword_config
@next keyword_sort
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: TO/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  Allows redirection of the output to another file.

  For example,

    @{b}TO=T:DirSize.TempOutput@{ub}

  will output all text to the file @{i}T:DirSize.TempOutput@{ui}.

  Any errors will still be printed on the console or wherever the output has
  been redirected to, for example, NIL:).

  Default: No redirection will take place. Text will be sent to the standard
  output.

@endnode
@node keyword_sort
@prev keyword_to
@next keyword_ascend
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: SORT/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  Allows the sorting of output  according  to  one  of  several  fields.  To
  specify which field, use one of the following keywords:

    @{u}Shortcut@{uu}  @{u}Keyword@{uu}  @{u}Action@{uu}
    O         OFF      Disable sorting
    P         PATH     Sort according to the names of directories
    S         SIZE     Sort according to the size of directories
    F         FILES    Sort according to the number of files in directories
    D         DIRS     Sort according to the number of sub-directories

  If sorting is enabled, you will not see any  output  until  all  specified
  directories have been scanned.

  An example:

  @{b}DirSize DH1:Music/TunesB DH1:Music/TunesC DH1:Music/TunesA SORT=PATH@{ub}

  Would output the directories in  alphabetical  order  (assuming  @{"ascending" link keyword_ascend}
  mode is enabled). Where @{b}SORT=PATH@{ub} is, @{b}SORT=P@{ub} could be substituted.

  For those you wish to know, I have used a (basic) binary  tree  (not  AVL)
  method  for sorting. In the case of @{b}DirSize@{ub}, these are more effecient than
  other algorithms such as @{i}insert sort@{ui}, @{i}bubble sort@{ui}, @{i}merge sort@{ui}, etc.

  Default: sorting is disabled.

  See also: @{"ASCEND/K" link keyword_ascend}

@endnode
@node keyword_ascend
@prev keyword_sort
@next envvar
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Keyword: ASCEND/K.@{uu}@{ub}

  This  keyword  complements  the  SORT  keyword.  It  enables  or  disables
  ascending mode for sorting. This keyword uses @{"boolean values" link boolean} to be enabled
  or disabled.

  When ascending mode is enabled, values such as 0, 1 and 2 will be  treated
  as  having  a  lower value than 3,4 and 5, and so on. The opposite is true
  when descending mode is on: higher values will be  shown  first  then  the
  lower values.

  Obviously, this keyword has no effect if @{"sorting" link keyword_sort} is not enabled!

  Default: ascending mode is on.

  See also: @{"SORT/K" link keyword_sort}, @{"boolean values" link boolean}

@endnode
@node envvar "Environment Variable"
@prev keyword_ascend
@next boolean
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Environment variable.@{uu}@{ub}

  Once you have decided on a favourite set-up  for  your  output,  etc.  you
  wouldn't  want to keep typing it in every time, @{b}DirSize@{ub} is called (although
  an alias could be made).

  Before reading the command line arguments, @{b}DirSize@{ub}  reads  an  environment
  variable  (as  set  up  by  @{b}SetEnv@{ub})  called  @{b}DIRSIZE@{ub}.  Any of the keywords
  available on the command line prompt can be placed here.  Only  @{"CONFIG" link keyword_config}  is
  ignored, to prevent potential, unbreakable recursion.

  To make the variable permanent, copy the @{b}DIRSIZE@{ub} file from @{b}ENV:@{ub} to @{b}ENVARC:@{ub}.

  Keywords on the command line will override any listed in  the  environment
  variable.  The only exception is the @{"directories" link keyword_dir} you wish to scan, whereby
  any additional directories will be added to a list.

  For clarity, the order in which everything is read is listed below:

    Main environment variable
    Second environment variable
    Command line

@endnode
@node boolean "Boolean keywords"
@prev envvar
@next examples
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Boolean keywords.@{uu}@{ub}

  Many of the keywords allow yes/no options. These are as follows:

    @{u}True values@{uu}  @{u}False values@{uu}
    Yes          No
    Y            N
    On           Off
    True         False
    1            0

  Any other value results in the default being taken.

  The reason behind this is to enable overriding of the environment variable
  keywords.

@endnode
@node examples "Example usage"
@prev boolean
@next limitations
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Example usage.@{uu}@{ub}

  @{b}DirSize@{ub}

  will output the total size of the current directory, including  all  files
  and automatically selecting a suitable sizing unit.

  @{b}DirSize archives BYTES KB@{ub}

  will size the directory archives using kilobytes  as  the  selected  unit.
  Note that although @{b}BYTES@{ub} was specified, @{b}KB@{ub} has precedence over it.

  @{b}DirSize archives/ PATTERN=#?.lha@{ub}

  will only count the files ending with .lha in the directory archives.

  @{b}DirSize DEVS: RECURSE=OFF SEP=0 FP=N@{ub}

  will find the total size of all the files in the DEVS:  directory  without
  printing any separators or floating points in the number output.

  As a final note, ensure there is enough stack space. 4096 bytes should  be
  enough for small to medium nested directories. I haven't tried to find the
  exact stack usage yet.

  See also: @{"FORMAT and FOOTFORMAT examples" link format_examples}

@endnode
@node limitations "Limitations and caveats"
@prev examples
@next bugs
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Limitations and caveats of DirSize.@{uu}@{ub}

  I  have not been able to try out @{b}DirSize@{ub} on anything larger than 100Mb. It
  is likely that on any directory (or, for that  matter,  total  size  of  a
  number  of directories) larger than 4Gb will produce garbage (most likely,
  an incorrect size).

  The technical reason for this is that a 32-bit number is used to store the
  size.  One  gigabyte  represented  in  bytes is 1,073,741,824. The highest
  unsigned 32-bit number possible to represent is  4,294,967,295,  which  is
  4Gb  less  one  byte.  If  demand  is high, I could use 64-bit numbers (my
  calculator approximates this to be 1.844674407E+19).  But,  for  the  time
  being, try to avoid summing the sizes of two RAID5 drives!

  A second, more minor caveat, is the decimal point in the  size  output  is
  not localised. It is set to a full-stop character ('.').

@endnode
@node bugs "Bug Reports"
@prev limitations
@next future
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Reporting bugs.@{uu}@{ub}

  First and foremost, ensure you have a sufficient stack available.  @{b}DirSize@{ub}
  is recursive, and a large number of nested directories may crash the system.

  If you come across  any  bugs,  please  report  them  by  sending  me  the
  following in as much detail as possible:

    * Characteristics of the bug, (e.g. program crash,  incorrect  directory
      sizes, etc.)

    * Your system:
        Machine type (e.g. A500, A1200, A4000T).
        Processor + co-processor (e.g. 68020+68882, 68030 no MMU).
        Memory available (chip ram, fast ram (16/32-bit), Retina).
        Graphics type (OCS, ECS, AGA, graphics card - type?).
        Kickstart/Workbench release (@{b}About@{ub} in Workbench will tell you this).
        Hardware peripherals.

    * Software you were running at  the  time  (try  to  re-create  the  bug
      without this software).

    * Take some time trying to re-create the bug (i.e.  cause  it  to  occur
      again).

    * Any other details you feel relevant (e.g. Mungwall/Enforcer  hits).  I
      don't  have  an  MMU,  so I cannot run Enforcer. Enforcer hits will be
      useful in tracking bugs.

  Send the report to me at the @{"address" link author} listed.

@endnode
@node future "Program Future"
@prev bugs
@next history
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}Future of DirSize.@{uu}@{ub}

  I have the following features planned for @{b}DirSize@{ub} in the near  future  (no
  particular order):

    * Graphic user-interface. Designed with Workbench  in  mind,  it  should
      show total size and current directory.

    * Localisation. Although it  is  unlikely  that  any  catalogs  will  be
      supplied  (I  don't  speak  any other language well enough to create a
      catalog file), I will ask for you for help.

    * Real-time updating display of 'size-so-far' in the Shell.

    * Stack checking - since a recursive function is used, a large number of
      directories may cause a stack-overflow and corrupt memory.

    * Maybe use 64-bit numbers for sizes larger than 4Gb (see @{"limitations" link limitations}).

    * Maximum size in @{"formatting strings" link keyword_format}.

    * More   inclusion/exclusion   keywords   for   files   (for    example,
      minimum/maxium size, date ranges, etc.).

    * Change the output of paths for sub-directories when  @{"verbose" link keyword_verbose}  mode  is
      enabled.

  The latest version of @{b}DirSize@{ub} can always be found on @{b}Aminet@{ub}.

  Further items maybe added at a later date. If you  have  any  suggestions,
  @{"contact me" link author} and I'll see what can be done.

@endnode
@node history "Program History"
@prev future
@next acknowledgements
@toc  main

  @{b}@{u}History of DirSize.@{uu}@{ub}

  1.0 (10 Jul. 1995) INTERNAL.       Program size: 4052 bytes.

        - First version. Only had @{"DIR/M" link keyword_dir} command line template.

  1.1 (12 Jul. 1995) INTERNAL.       Program size: 4704 bytes.

        - Added BYTES, KILOBYTES,  MEGABYTES,  GIGABYTES  and  AUTO  keyword
          options. See @{"size types" link keyword_sizetype}.

  1.2 (13 Sep. 1995) INTERNAL.       Program size: 5260 bytes.

        - Names are enclosed in quotes to avoid confusion if there  contains
          a space.
        - Added a version string.
        - Added a file and directory counter.

  1.3  (5 Jan. 1996) INTERNAL.       Program size: 5628 bytes.

        - Removed some debugging statements I left in.
        - Added  pattern  matching.  Only  works  on  files  matching  given
          pattern.

  1.4  (2 Aug. 1996) PUBLIC RELEASE. Program size: 5392 bytes.

        - Made some optimisations (compare the size with 1.3).
        - Removed a function which is no longer needed (it also contained  a
          Mungwall hit since version 1.0).
        - Altered text output. Now it is clearer and less verbose.
        - Added ctrl-c checking whilst recurring through directories.
        - Added an AmigaGuide® document.
        - Made an Installer script.
        - Finally released it!

  1.5 (24 Aug. 1996) PUBLIC RELEASE.  Program size: 5576 bytes.

        - Fixed an error in this document, which  caused  Enforcer  hits  on
          some (all?) machines. Thanks to Mika Lundell for reporting this.
        - Now gives error messages.
        - Pattern  matching  for  directories  implemented.  @{"NOWILD" link keyword_wildcard}  keyword
          disables this feature.
        - @{"WILD" link keyword_pattern} keyword renamed to @{"PATTERN" link keyword_pattern} for clarity.
        - Altered text output (again!).
        - Some major optimisations made, resulting in  a  size  decrease  to
          compensate for new features.
        - Conversion  to  gigabytes  in  automatic mode has been temporarily
          disabled. See @{"limitations" link limitations}.
        - Sizes in units of kilobytes and larger now have a fractional part.
          For example, a directory of 45000Kb will no longer be displayed as
          43Mb, but as 43.94Mb.
        - Some minor bugs fixed. One being, when pressing CTRL-C, the entire
          program  quits,  rather  than aborting the current directory being
          scanned.

  1.6 (30 Oct. 1996) PUBLIC RELEASE.  Program size: 9440 bytes.

        - @{b}DirSize@{ub} can now be made resident.  (Actually,  I  think  it  could
          before,  but  I  never  explicitly  said to compile as residential
          code).
        - Matching specified files (no  wildcards)  is  allowed  in  @{"PATTERN" link keyword_pattern}
          keyword.
        - Separators are only displayed in sizes if  there  is  no  floating
          point.
        - Added support for an @{"environment variable" link envvar}.
        - Added following keywords:
            @{"CONFIG" link keyword_config}
            @{"FLOATINGPOINT" link keyword_floatingpoint}
            @{"SEPARATORS" link keyword_separators}
            @{"RECURSE" link keyword_recurse}
            @{"FOOTER" link keyword_footer}
            @{"WILDCARD" link keyword_wildcard} (Replaces NOWILD keyword).
        - @{"BLOCKS" link keyword_sizetype} unit implemented.
        - Changed the output for the last time. If you're not happy with it,
          change it! See @{"FORMAT" link keyword_format} and @{"FOOTFORMAT" link keyword_format} keywords.
        - If  no  directories  were  specified,  the  path  of  the  current
          directory is printed instead of the text, "Current directory"

  1.7  (5 Feb. 1997) PUBLIC RELEASE.  Program size: 11180 bytes.

        - Added @{"HEADER" link keyword_header} keyword.
        - Footer (if enabled) will be printed even if ctrl-c was pressed.
        - @{"CONFIG" link keyword_config} @{"environment  variable" link envvar}  is  read  before  the  command  line
          arguments.  Hence  any  keywords on the command line will override
          those in either environment variable
        - @{"DIRS" link keyword_dir} keyword is no longer overridden by environment variables  and
          command   line.  Instead,  they  are  put  in  a  list  so  preset
          directories can be set  up.  This  can  be  useful  when  used  in
          conjunction with the @{"CONFIG" link keyword_config} keyword.
        - Added @{"TO" link keyword_to} keyword.
        - "Please insert volume..." requester is supressed when looking  for
          environment variables.
        - Bug fix: output can now have a length of one character.
        - Added @{"SORT" link keyword_sort} and @{"ASCEND" link keyword_ascend} keywords.
        - Added @{"VERBOSE" link keyword_verbose} keyword.
        - Fixed bug where @{"footer" link keyword_footer} would not appear when set to  1,  and  only
          one directory is scanned.

@endnode
